             was indicted for <rs id="t18271025-250-off1428" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-off1428" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-off1428" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18271025-250-cd1429" type="crimeDate">25th of October</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18271025-250-off1428 t18271025-250-cd1429"></join>, 1 box, value 5s.; 3 gowns, value 6s.; 4 petticoats, value 3s.; 2 shifts, value 4s.; 6 pairs of stockings, value 6s.; 6 aprons, value 6s., and 1 apron, value 2s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18271025-250-victim1295" type="victimName">
                  Esther 
                  Mackreth
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-victim1295" type="surname" value="Mackreth"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-victim1295" type="given" value="Esther"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-victim1295" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18271025-250-off1428 t18271025-250-victim1295"></join>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>ESTHER MACKRETH. I am <rs id="t18271025-250-viclabel1430" type="occupation">single</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18271025-250-victim1295 t18271025-250-viclabel1430"></join>. On the 25th of October I had left my situation to go into the country, and employed Grey to fetch my boxes - he keeps a horse and cart; he received them at No. 4, Charlotte-street, Blackfriars', to take to Crown-court, Goswell-street, but I only received one box there - the other contained the articles stated in the indictment and others.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-250-person1296">
                  JAMES 
                  GREY
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1296" type="surname" value="GREY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1296" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I received two boxes from the prosecutrix on Thursday; as I went along I found my horse lame - I stopped at a farrier's in St. John-street, as I could not get on; I delivered both boxes at the <placeName id="t18271025-250-crimeloc1431">Queen's Head public-house, St. John-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18271025-250-crimeloc1431" type="placeName" value="Queen's Head public-house, St. John-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18271025-250-crimeloc1431" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18271025-250-off1428 t18271025-250-crimeloc1431"></join>; I gave them into the prisoner's care, while I took the horse out; he had been in my employ. I returned after the horse was shod, and he and the box were gone.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-250-person1297">
                  WILLIAM 
                  CATER
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1297" type="surname" value="CATER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1297" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1297" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep the Queen's Head. I remember the prisoner and prosecutor bringing two boxes to my house - he left the prisoner there with two boxes - I saw the prisoner take one away - that was a blue box; he left the other on the table; I took it into the bar for safety: he left my house about six o'clock - he was neither drunk nor sober.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-250-person1298">
                  MARY 
                  EYRE
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1298" type="surname" value="EYRE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1298" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1298" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. West, of Saffron-hill - the prisoner lodged there. On Thursday evening he came into the outer passage, sat the box on the mat, and wanted to take it up stairs; my master was not at home - I said master would not allow any boxes to be taken up - he then took it away, saying he must take it to his sister's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-250-person1299">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WATSON
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1299" type="surname" value="WATSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1299" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1299" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner on Thursday night, about eleven o'clock, and asked what he had done with the box - he said he had been knocked down, and it was taken from him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18271025-250-person1300">
                  ABRAHAM 
                  GRIFFITHS
               <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1300" type="surname" value="GRIFFITHS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1300" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18271025-250-person1300" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was brought to me at the watch-house, and said he was knocked down in Wilderness-row, and the box taken from him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. Grey told me to take one of the boxes home; I had been drinking, and found myself rather stupid; I took it to my lodging, thinking to take it home in the morning - the young woman would not take it in; I took it away, and set it down while I stopped for a certain purpose, and it was taken.</p>
               <p>JAMES GREY. I did not desire him to take them home, but to take care of them till I returned.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18271025-250-verdict1432" type="verdictDescription">
